Soldering stand with the basics in a nice little package.

Featuring:

  • a spot for a 25mm cubed sponge
  • soldering spool holder that can handle 2 spools with a total height of 55mm
  • channels for easy access to the solder while the spools are in the stand
  • a hole for a soldering iron holder (the coil that holds the soldering iron on most kits)

Contains an STL and a SKP file in the package. The SKP file has labels for the features.

Take Measurements of the Items

When making a stand of this type taking good measurements of every basic dimension of the things you are putting into it is crucial. Make sure to overestimate more than underestimate if you are going to be removing the items or wanting them to move around when in use. I took the measurements of the cube and the height, outer dimension, and inner dimensions of the spools.

Build From the Ground Up

Start with a square that will hold all of the parts depth and width-wise. I raised the surface of this square 2mm because I wanted this much of a gap between the bottom and any of the items. Then I drew a couple circles for the spools and added offset circles for the channels. Channels are a bit difficult to explain in text but looking at the model can probably help. Then raise the outer part of surface and the inner circle for the spools to the highest dimension you need, leaving the surface where the spools sit on alone.

And Back Down for the Sponge

The square for the sponge was drawn with 2mm borders on 3 sides except for the most front-facing border. This was crucial for the facing "ledge" keeping the sponge from sitting in a hole, per-say. So adding in an extra 2mm in depth between the back and the front of the square (making this dimension 27mm instead of 25mm) was the difference. This surface was then lowered by 10mm. Then the offset 2mm comes into play. I drew the closest border back this far (which would have been done normally if making a pocket) creating a square no longer touching the outsides of the model. This creates the surface in the front. Then lower the square's surface 15mm for the rest of inside for the sponge's spot.

Smaller Details

The base was expanded because it helps prevent tipping of the stand with the weight of the soldering iron. I did so late in the modeling process because I like the angular look and having a big surface on the top and in front of the spools, etc... looks funny to me. This also hinders the features of the sponge. These dimensions were as big as my printer could handle so if you still experience tipping of the stand I would suggest adhesive or modifying this design.

The hole for the soldering iron holder was centered on the left "half" of the stand behind the sponge. It has a 2mm hole on the top. However, if it ever needs to be secured by a nut, a 6mm hole on the bottom all the way to the top is a good idea.

The solder spools are based off of ones from Radioshack.
I have no idea what the part which holds the soldering iron is actually "called" so maybe someone can help me out with this info. Also, this part of the design was actually modified compared to the version I printed because I had an unusual part to work with, meaning I have not tested it. I made the hole in this fashion based off of the general public's accessibility. I would appreciate it if I can find out whether this works or not so I can modify it.

description.text:
DISCLAIMER!!! this is potentially a dangerous or even deadly part to 3d print and use, someone rightfully pointed this out to me. So if you print this file you are taking full responsibility for whatever happens due to usage of this part.

i lost my golf mk3's ?rubber? engine compartment gear globe due to my car's old age... so my shifter had a lot of play.. when i say a lot i mean like 8 cm before i even felt resistance.

EDIT: apparently it's called "Deflection Shaft, gearshift mechanism ball" or in german "Kugel der Umlenkwelle vom Schaltgestänge"

I searched everywhere for a replacement part, couldn't find it, and then i realized... i have a 3D printer and ABS filament is a thing.

So here it is, the engine compartment gear globe replacement. Made it in 3 sizes, loose fit, good fit and super tight fit. Pick one, print twice and use 2 decent cable ties to hold it in place, and enjoy high accuracy shifting like the car is new again.

I can confirm that this works for golf mk3 and polo mk3 with 1.6 cylinder engines.

DON'T PRINT THIS IN PLA, IT WILL MELT IN THE ENGINE COMPARTMENT.. Trust me.. i know.

I printed this in ABS @ 0,3 layer height, without a heated bed, with an e3dLite hot end @ 235degrees centigrade. I used decent 2 sided adhesion tape to get it to stick to the build plate... took me 3 tries to get it right, your mileage may vary.

Because this is such a critical component in your car, i tested this for over a year before publishing this thing...and it still works (your mileage may vary, print at your own risk).. i shall try to post pictures soonish.

If someone knows the right name for this part, pls tell me so i can update the filename. Thanks.

description.text:
This spacer is a derivative work of Thing 14548.  I've created this derivative solely for the purpose of providing others with an OpenSCAD description of the part so that they can fine tune it for their particular printer and bearings.  That way, a good fitting spacer which won't rattle can be produced.
Also these spacers can be used on the Y-axis carriage as well as the Z-axis.  As with the Z-axis, you would be replacing the press-fit adjustable bushings with these linear bearings.

See Thing 14548 http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:14548 for details. To adjust the spacer, you will likely want to change the two parameters EXTRA and t in the OpenSCAD source file. EXTRA sets how large to make the inside hole in the spacer relative to the outside dimension of the bearing. It is a multiplicative factor set to 1.04. Make larger or smaller so as to get a good fit with minimal play. The parameter t is the thickness of your panels. Again, adjust so as to get a good fit.
  • Print out four spacers for the Z-axis carriage and two more for the Y-axis carriage if you will be adding linear bearings to it as well. Use the "multiply" section of skeinforge with 3 columns and 2 rows in order to get 6. However, you may first want to print just one as you adjust the fit.
  • Slide a spacer onto each bearing. Secure one end with a 9/16" clip.
  • Install the bearing and clip on the other end with another 9/16" clip.

title: Makergear M2 Hinged V4 Filament Drive

description.text:
This is a modified spring loaded hinged version of the original V4 Filament Drive for the Makergear M2.

My original drive (printed in PETG) wore out (the springiness of the tension of the bottom of the drive) so I designed this hinged version to overcome it wearing out again. I also added the springs because I hate having to adjust the screw tension for different filaments. I also added two screws for the tension to hopefully get a move even tension on the bearing.

I used (2) M4x25 screws/nuts, some cut down springs from the hardware store (sorry no idea what rate they are), and a finish nail (4D maybe) for the hinge pin.

The fan mounting point on this is offset so if you run the stock fans you may have to add a longer bolt and spacer to use them. I do not run an extruder fans and I use a blower motor for a bed fan (because they are quiet) so my mounts are different than the stock version.

This is the blower motor I use (http://www.amazon.com/uxcell%C2%AE-Brushless-Sleeve-Bearing-Cooling-50mmx15mm/dp/B00W8W8LMM?ie)

Made a general purpose bearing using commercial 3/16 chrome ball bearing to keep my multiple filaments spools aligned and easy for the printer to pull the filament.  The design is parameter driven from a text file with few parameters: Ball bearing size, inner hole diameter and outer diameter.  The zip file contains the general purpose round bearing and the filament bearing which adds the larger outer spokes to fit the spool.  Files supplied are openSCAD to build your own and STL. The outer part also prints a small piece that fits in a slot to hold the bearing in.  Both the inner and outer have cut outs to insert the bearing.  No glue is normally required.  I have always had to do some minor cleanup on the inner and outer race to remove volunteer ABS.   The bearings are from Amazon about $4 for 100.  The design uses 15 ball bearings.

description.text: Need a transition section that's not available commercially? Want a hollow transition for a payload or electronics bay and you can only get Balsa? Notes:

Very Challenging to Print. Requires Simplify3D to print effectively. The issue is that you need multiple perimeters where the body tubes meet the transition to ensure that you get a one piece part. You can try printing the entire transition with enough perimeters to support the shoulders, but then you get an excessively heavy part. I am able to successful print these using 6 different processes to increase perimeters where needed and still keep most of the transition very light using 2 layers. I use the section tool to examine how the layers are stacking at the tube ends.

I print them in ABS for resilience. Can be acetone vapor smoothed for better surface and to assure good layer bonding.

description.text:
TIRED OF YOUR Z-AXIS CRASHING DOWN WHEN YOUR PRINT IS COMPLETE.
WHAT YOU NEED IS THE AFORDABLE PORTABLE Z-AXIS BRAKE SYSTEM FROM SLIP-CO. NOW FOR THE LOW LOW PRICE OF NOTHING YOU CAN DOWNLOAD THE FILES AND PRINT THE PARTS TO MODIFY YOUR M2 TO THE SEXY YET FUNCTIONAL Z-AXIS BRAKE SYSTEM.

Some additional parts are required:

You will need 7 to 10 8MMX3MM N50 magnets. if you search for " 8MMX3MM N50 " on ebay they are cheap and plentiful.

You will need a 8-32 set screw 3/8-1/2" long to go in the cross hole on the handle to keep it from spinning off. (It is better to tap the hole before putting the screw in.)

Notes:

Printed in PLA . I have found when printing threads PLA work well. Also pla is high strength and this application is not a high temp or outside application so it works well.

Installation

After your parts are done you will need to put 6 of the magnets in the base. Make sure they are all facing the same way so when another magnet is passed over them they all either repel or attract.

Place 1 to 3 magnets in the bottom of the handle. I found that 1 sufficed on my setup with a Mic 6 plate but you may need more based on your setup to keep the axis from falling.
Be sure that when you put the magnet in the handle it is facing the direction that it will be attracted to the all plastic side of the base.

Put your 8-32 set screw in the knob. It is better to tap the hole first.

Install with the base with magnets facing down. Screw the knob on to the z-axis shaft. Be sure that is loose to the base and secure with the set screw.

When running it makes a clicking sound. If you modify the base to be a tight fit with your machine you can make this go away. I built the added clearance in so it would fit everyones machine. I have included the design files to aid in this change.

Feedback is appreciated.

description.text:
This is a Home lock piece for the Geeetech G2s. A lot of people have issues getting the printer to keep steppers enabled after printing especially with Simplify 3d. This option acts as a backup to make sure that when the printer is given the command to home all axes at the end of the print, even if steppers are disabled, it will hold the spider in the home position rather than have the hot end crash into the printed object.

All 3 trolleys must have the clips installed to be fully effective and function as intended.

I was wanting this done fast so I printed at 0.3 at 80mm/s. Doesn't make for the best quallity but it gets the job done fast haha, so please excuse the poor quallity prints in the picture.
